1. Introduction

The dataset we used is suicide rates compiled dataset pulled from four other datasets linked by time and place, and was built to find signals correlated to increased suicide rates among different cohorts globally, across the socio-economic spectrum.

The suicide rate are from 2016-2021. We conducted two analysis:
  1. We looked at suicide rates and provided statistical analysis and insights based on the distribution of suicide and the influencing factors, e.g., continent and country, age, etc.
  2. Since after 2012, [The World Happiness Report] (https://worldhappiness.report) publishes dataset annually, we aimed at exploring the relationship between the suicide rates and WHO report.

Objective: the idea is to display the distribution of all three series and look at the shapes. The goal is also to learn how to plot using R and how to customize and combine plots. Eventually, the final result should look like:

1.2 Plotting the main densities

Just plotting the 10 points for each dataset wont help much. When looking at the density distribution, one can observe the shape, if it is bell-shaped or not, and how they compare to each other. You have already learned to use the dnorm() function which produces the density of a normal distribution with a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1.

  • Use this function to plot a series of x values in order to obtain a smooth curve (e.g. 100 values from -5 to 5).

Tip

seq() is a very neat function that you should memorize, remember to check its help page with ?seq. The argument length.out should help to have a smooth line.

# Write your answer here
x <- seq(-5, 5, length.out = 100)
y <- dnorm(x)

tibble(x,y) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x,y)) +
  geom_line()

garden_t <- garden %>%

[Hamed: ] Then, we find the density of the min and max of gardens values and put them into two columns

garden_range <- garden_t %>% 
  group_by(gardens) %>%
  summarise(min_density = min(density(ozone_concentrations)$x, na.rm= TRUE), max_density = max(density(ozone_concentrations)$x, na.rm= TRUE))

1.3 Plotting Quantile-Quantile comparison to the normal distribution

A Q-Q plot allows you to see how the quantiles of two distributions fit. In our case, we want to compare each of the gardens distribution to the normal distribution. Use the function qqnorm() and add the ideal line with qqline(). When the dots are close to the plain line, then the distribution follows the normal one.

# Write your answer here
#gardenA
qqnorm(garden$gardenA, frame = FALSE)
qqline(garden$gardenA, col = "green")

#gardenB
qqnorm(garden$gardenB, frame = FALSE)
qqline(garden$gardenB, col = "green")

#gardenC
qqnorm(garden$gardenC, frame = FALSE)
qqline(garden$gardenC, col = "green")

Try to draw the Q-Q plot with ggplot. The stat_qq() function provided by ggplot might be helpful, by default it uses the normal distribution.

To enhance the way of drawing a Q-Q plot:

  • scale the ozone concentration for each garden
  • plot the scaled sample quantiles against the theoretical quantiles (stat_qq).
  • add the line \(y=x\) (geom_abline).

Tip

the function scale() allows to center a distribution as z-scores:

  • mean centered on 0
  • standard deviation of 1

1.6 Statistical tests to assess normality

Use the Shapiro test for the three datasets, using \(\alpha=0.05\).

  • What can you conclude about these 3 distributions?
  • Are they following the normal distribution?
  • Does it fit your visual expectations?
# Write your answer here
gardenA <- tidy(shapiro.test(garden$gardenA))
gardenB <- tidy(shapiro.test(garden$gardenB))
gardenC <- tidy(shapiro.test(garden$gardenC))
rbind(gardenA, gardenB, gardenC)

Tip

Adding notches to a box plot allows you to visually evaluate confidence intervals (by default 95% CI) for the medians. Use geom_boxplot() and set notch = TRUE. If the notches do not overlap, this is evidence that the medians are different.

# Write your answer here
ggplot(wings)+
  geom_boxplot(aes(x = location, y = size), notch = TRUE)

2.4 Compare the two means

Before comparing the two means, we need to ensure that both distributions are normal in order to determine which test we should use.

  1. Which test should be used to test the normality? Are A and B following a normal distribution?

Tip

  • Try to stick to the tidyverse way of doing and use tibbles. Think about setting a grouping variable and nest the tibble.
  • To apply your test to a subset, define a new column using mutate and use the function map() from the purrr package to map your statistical function to each subset. (You will learn more how to use the function map() next time)
  • Finally, use the tidy() function from the broom package to get a nice output.
# Write your answer here
wings %>%
  group_by(location) %>% 
  nest() %>%
  mutate(statF = map(data, ~shapiro.test(wings$size)), tidy = map(statF,tidy)) %>% 
  unnest(tidy)
